Hereâ€™s the simple, practical way to **get / set / delete `localStorage` in React** ðŸ‘‡
(Itâ€™s just browser JS â€” React doesnâ€™t change the API.)

---

## âœ… Set item in `localStorage`

```js
localStorage.setItem("user", "John");
```

If youâ€™re storing **objects or arrays**, stringify them:

```js
const user = { name: "John", age: 25 };
localStorage.setItem("user", JSON.stringify(user));
```

---

## ðŸ“¥ Get item from `localStorage`

```js
const user = localStorage.getItem("user");
```

If itâ€™s JSON:

```js
const user = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("user"));
```

âš ï¸ `getItem` returns `null` if the key doesnâ€™t exist.

---

## âŒ Delete item from `localStorage`

```js
localStorage.removeItem("user");
```

---

## ðŸ§¹ Clear *all* localStorage (be careful)

```js
localStorage.clear();
```

---

## ðŸ” Using `localStorage` with React state (common pattern)

```js
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function App() {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(() => {
    const savedUser = localStorage.getItem("user");
    return savedUser ? JSON.parse(savedUser) : null;
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    if (user) {
      localStorage.setItem("user", JSON.stringify(user));
    } else {
      localStorage.removeItem("user");
    }
  }, [user]);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setUser({ name: "John" })}>
        Save User
      </button>
      <button onClick={() => setUser(null)}>
        Delete User
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

---

## ðŸ§  Pro tips

* `localStorage` is **synchronous** â†’ donâ€™t overuse it in performance-critical code
* Data persists **even after refresh or browser close**
* Never store **passwords or tokens without security considerations**

